---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Scrabble Rack Leave Analysis — What to Keep After Every Play"
  description="Master rack leave analysis in Scrabble. Learn which tiles to keep, synergy combinations, vowel-consonant balance, and how leave quality determines your next turn's potential."
  keywords="scrabble rack leave, leave analysis scrabble, what tiles to keep scrabble, rack management, synergy tiles scrabble, scrabble tile balance, rack leave strategy"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Article","headline":"Scrabble Rack Leave Analysis — What to Keep After Every Play","description":"Master rack leave analysis in Scrabble. Learn which tiles to keep, synergy combinations, and how leave quality determines your next turn.","datePublished":"2026-06-30","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"ScrabbleWordsFinder.com","url":"https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"ScrabbleWordsFinder.com"},"mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/scrabble-leave-analysis-guide"}})} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What is rack leave in Scrabble?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Rack leave is the tiles remaining on your rack after you make a play. If you have SATIREN and play RAINS (5 tiles), your leave is TE. Good leave analysis means choosing plays that leave strong combinations for your next draw."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What are the best tiles to keep in Scrabble?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The best leave tiles are those in the SATIRE/RETINA family: S, A, T, I, R, E, N. These form the most bingos. Keep 2-3 of these after every play. Avoid keeping duplicates, Q without U access, or V/W combinations."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How many vowels should you keep in your rack leave?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Aim for a 2:1 consonant-to-vowel ratio in your leave. After a 5-tile play, keeping 1 vowel and 1 consonant is typical. Two vowels in a 2-tile leave is risky — you'll likely draw more vowels and get stuck."}}]})} />
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1"><a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a><span class="mx-1">›</span><span class="text-gray-300">Strategy</span></nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Scrabble Rack Leave Analysis — What to Keep After Every Play</h1>
      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400"><time datetime="2026-06-30">June 30, 2026</time><span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span><span>6 min read</span><span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span><a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a></div>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">Every Scrabble play is two decisions: what you play and what you keep. Most players focus only on score. Tournament players know that the tiles you leave behind determine your next three turns. A 5-point sacrifice now for a better leave can yield 20+ extra points over the next two draws.</p>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">SATIRE</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Best Leave Combo</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">2:1</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Consonant:Vowel Ratio</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">+20 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Good Leave Advantage</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The Synergy Tiles — S, A, T, I, R, E, N</h2>
      <p>These seven letters produce more bingos than any other combination. Tournament databases show that racks containing 5+ of these letters hit bingos over 60% of the time. When choosing between two plays of similar score, keep the one that leaves more SATIREN tiles.</p>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-500/40 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">S</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">1pt · Hooks</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-500/40 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">A</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">1pt · Vowel</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-500/40 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">T</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">1pt · Common</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-500/40 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">I</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">1pt · Vowel</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-500/40 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">R</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">1pt · Endings</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-500/40 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">E</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">1pt · Flexible</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-500/40 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">N</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">1pt · -ING/-TION</span></span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Tiles to Dump First</h2>
      <p>Some tiles actively harm your rack synergy. Prioritise playing these even if it means scoring 5-10 fewer points:</p>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10"><p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⚠️ Duplicate Vowels</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Two of the same vowel (AA, II, UU) clog your rack. Play one immediately — don't keep both hoping for consonants.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10"><p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⚠️ V and W Together</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">V=4 and W=4 both need vowels to function. Keeping both starves you of consonant flexibility. Dump one per turn.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10"><p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⚠️ Q Without U Access</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">If no U is visible on the board or your rack, consider exchanging Q. The 10 points it offers rarely compensate for 3+ turns of dead weight.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10"><p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⚠️ Multiple High-Point Tiles</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">J+X or Z+Q together is a nightmare. You can't use both in one play and they block bingo potential. Play one, keep the other.</p></div>
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Leave Evaluation by Size</h2>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">1-tile leave:</span> Best leaves are S, blank, E, or R. Worst are V, U, or Q. With one tile, you draw 6 — so almost any single SATIREN letter gives you bingo potential.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">2-tile leave:</span> Ideal: one vowel + one consonant from SATIREN (e.g., ER, AT, IN). Avoid two vowels or two of the same letter. ER leave outperforms QU leave by 15+ points on average next turn.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">3-tile leave:</span> The sweet spot for bingo setup. ING, ERS, ATE, and ENT are elite 3-tile leaves. You draw 4 tiles — enough to complete most 7-letter words with the right combination.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Key Insight</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">A play scoring 30 with a leave of ER is usually better than a play scoring 38 with a leave of QV. The <span class="text-white font-medium">expected value of your next turn</span> matters more than maximising this turn. Think two moves ahead.</p>
      </div>
      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/rack-management-basics/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group"><span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Rack Management Basics</span></a>
          <a href="/blog/rack-leave-explained/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group"><span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Rack Leave Explained</span></a>
          <a href="/blog/vowel-heavy-rack-solutions/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group"><span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Vowel-Heavy Rack Solutions</span></a>
        </div>
      </aside>
      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-900/20 to-cyan-900/20 border border-blue-800 rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-blue-300 font-medium">🔤 Analyse your rack leave instantly — free Scrabble solver with tile probability</p>
          <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700 text-white text-sm font-semibold transition-colors shadow-sm">Open Word Finder →</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center"><a href="/blog/" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Back to all articles</a></div>
    </article>
  </div>
</BlogLayout>
